To add a graph that shows your expenses in Jetpack Compose Material3 in an alternating style between daily, weekly, monthly, and yearly, you can use the `LineChart` composable function provided by the `Charts` library. Here's an example of how to use the `LineChart` function and how to alternate the data based on selected time intervals:

```kotlin
@Composable
fun ExpenseGraph(expenseData: List<Expense>, selectedInterval: TimeInterval) {
    val data = generateData(expenseData, selectedInterval)
    LineChart(
        data = data,
        xAxis = ChartAxis.Labelled(data.xLabels),
        yAxis = ChartAxis.Labelled(data.yLabels),
        selection = Selection.None,
        backgroundColor = MaterialTheme.colors.background,
        lineColors = listOf(MaterialTheme.colors.primary),
        lineWidth = 2.dp,
        insetValue = 32.dp,
        legend = null
    )
}

private fun generateData(expenseData: List<Expense>, interval: TimeInterval): ChartData {
    // Generate data and labels for the selected interval
    val data = when (interval) {
        TimeInterval.Daily -> generateDataForInterval(expenseData, ChronoUnit.DAYS)
        TimeInterval.Weekly -> generateDataForInterval(expenseData, ChronoUnit.WEEKS)
        TimeInterval.Monthly -> generateDataForInterval(expenseData, ChronoUnit.MONTHS)
        TimeInterval.Yearly -> generateDataForInterval(expenseData, ChronoUnit.YEARS)
    }

    // Generate labels for the x-axis
    val xLabels = when (interval) {
        TimeInterval.Daily -> data.xValues.map { it.dayOfMonth.toString() }
        TimeInterval.Weekly -> data.xValues.map { "Week ${it.get(IsoFields.WEEK_OF_WEEK_BASED_YEAR)}" }
        TimeInterval.Monthly -> data.xValues.map { Month.of(it.monthValue).name.take(3) }
        TimeInterval.Yearly -> data.xValues.map { it.year.toString() }
    }

    // Generate labels for the y-axis
    val yLabels = data.yValues.map { it.toString() }

    return ChartData(
        xLabels = xLabels,
        yLabels = yLabels,
        xValues = data.xValues,
        points = data.yValues.mapIndexed { i, value -> Point(i, value.toFloat()) },
    )
}

private fun generateDataForInterval(expenseData: List<Expense>, interval: TemporalUnit): ChartDataEntry {
    val start = expenseData.firstOrNull()?.date ?: Instant.now()
    val end = expenseData.lastOrNull()?.date ?: Instant.now()
    val tempDate = LocalDate.ofInstant(start, ZoneOffset.UTC).with(TemporalAdjusters.startOf(interval))
    val endTempDate = LocalDate.ofInstant(end, ZoneOffset.UTC)
    val xVals = mutableListOf<LocalDate>()
    val yVals = mutableListOf<Double>()
    while (!tempDate.isAfter(endTempDate)) {
        val expensesForPeriod = expenseData.filter { LocalDate.ofInstant(it.date, ZoneOffset.UTC).isBefore(tempDate.plus(1, interval)) }
        val totalExpenses = expensesForPeriod.sumOf { it.amount }
        xVals.add(tempDate)
        yVals.add(totalExpenses)
        tempDate = tempDate.plus(1, interval)
    }
    return ChartDataEntry(xVals, yVals)
}

enum class TimeInterval {
    Daily,
    Weekly,
    Monthly,
    Yearly
}
```

In this example, the `ExpenseGraph` composable function takes in the expense data and the selected interval as its parameters. It then generates the data and labels for the selected interval using the `generateData` function, which creates a `ChartData` object containing the x and y axis labels and data points. 

The `generateDataForInterval` function generates the data for the selected interval by filtering the expense data and calculating the total expenses for each time interval. The x-axis labels and values are created based on the selected interval, while the y-axis labels are generated based on the total expenses for each interval.

The `LineChart` composable function is then used to display the generated graph, with various customization options such as line color and width. 

To switch between the different time intervals, you can use a `RadioButton` or `SegmentedControl` to update the `selectedInterval` parameter of the `ExpenseGraph`.
